column31: Hydrogen and stupidity are the two most abundant materials in the universe
Sodium is the primary element in salt
Silicon semiconductors on a computer processor
Chlorine tablet used to clean pool bacteria
Argon gas is used inside of light bulbs
Potassium is commonly used in fertilizers
Calcium is one of the most abundant elements in the human body
Selenium in glass gives a red tint
Bromine provides flame resilience for printed circuit boards
Krypton is used in fluorescent light bulbs
Niobium is used in crafting steel for jet engines
Technetium is found in extremely small quantities in urnaium ore
Palladium is used in catalytic converters
Indium is used to create touchscreens and other electronic device's screens
Antimony is used to create infrared detectors
Tellurium is used ito create CDs and DVDs
Iodine is used in creating printing inks and dyes
Cerium is used to create the flint of lighters
Praseodymium is used for stage lighting and projection
Neodymium is used to create magnets
Promethium is used to create batteries for pacemakers
Samarium is used to create microwaves
Europium is used to create European currency
Gadolinium is used to create computer hard drive memory disks
Terbium is used to create computer solid state drive memory devices
Dysprosium is used primarily for turbines and electric vehicles
Erbium is used in glass for welding and saftey goggles
Thulium is used to create x-ray machines
Ytterbium is used to create memory devices
Hafnium is used to create control rods for nuclear submarines
Iridium is used to create compass bearings
Thallium used to be used in rodent poisons
Bismuth is used to create yellow cosmetics
Polonium powered Luna E-1| which carried the first rovers to the moon
Thorium helps increase refractive index in glass for high-end camera lens
Plutonium was used to create the first atomic bombs and is still used in modern nuclear weapons
Americium is used to create fire alarms
Curium is used to create satellite technology
Californium is used to create gold and silver metal detectors
Einsteinium was studied in particle accelerators by Albert Einstein
Fermium is named after Enrico Fermi
Mendelevium is named after Dimitri Mendeleev
Nobelium is named after Alfred Nobel| the founder of the Nobel Prize
Lawrencium is named after Ernest Lawrence
Rutherfordium is named after Ernest Rutherford
Seaborgium is named after Glenn T| Seaborg
Bohrium is named after Niels Bohr
Hassium was first created in Hesse| Germany
Meitnerium is named after physicist Lise Meitner
Roentgenium is named after Wilhelm Conrad Roentgen| the discoverer of x-rays
Copernicium is named after Renaissance scientist Nicolaus Copernicus
Nihonium was discovered by scientists at RIKEN (Science Institute) in Japan
Flerovium was discovered at Russian physicist Georgy Flerov's Joint Institute for Nuclear Research
Livermorium was discovered Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory
Tennessine was discovered at Oak Ridge National Laboratory in Tennessee
Oganesson was named after Russian nuclear physicist Yuri Oganessian for his contributions to transactinide element research
